Introduction to GitHub

GitHub is a cloud-based platform used for storing, managing, and sharing source code. 
It is built on top of Git, a version control system that helps developers track changes in their projects.

Key Features of GitHub:
Code Repository – Stores project files and source code.
Version Control – Tracks every change made to the code.
Collaboration – Multiple developers can work on the same project.
Branching and Merging – Create separate branches for new features and merge them later.
Pull Requests – Review and discuss code before merging.
Issue Tracking – Report bugs and manage tasks.
Open Source Projects – Contribute to projects from around the world.
GitHub Actions – Automate testing and deployment.
